<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/AE58F21F-3622-4382-97BB-1359BD183E9F"><gtr:id>AE58F21F-3622-4382-97BB-1359BD183E9F</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Glasgow</gtr:name><gtr:department>School of Physics and Astronomy</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>University Avenue</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Glasgow</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>G12 8QQ</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>Scotland</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/AE58F21F-3622-4382-97BB-1359BD183E9F"><gtr:id>AE58F21F-3622-4382-97BB-1359BD183E9F</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Glasgow</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>University Avenue</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Glasgow</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>G12 8QQ</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>Scotland</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/1979B92D-6C6A-4C4A-85F4-E0A150E247A8"><gtr:id>1979B92D-6C6A-4C4A-85F4-E0A150E247A8</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Alison</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Bates</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=PP%2FC001257%2F1"><gtr:id>1F1C2975-D911-44DD-9A4F-EB79BE3064AB</gtr:id><gtr:title>First Measurement of the CKM Triangle Angle gamma at LHCb</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>PP/C001257/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>The Large Hadron Collider (LHC) is a proton-proton collider at CERN which will start operation in spring 2007. The four LHC experiments will analyse these collisions and will test the current understanding of fundamental particles and their interactions, the Standard Model. LHCb will specifically focus on the understanding of CP violation, a small asymmetry in the behaviour of particles and anti-particles, which is thought to be the cause of a universe dominated by matter - rather than anti-matter. The LHCb detector has been designed to study the production and decay of particles containing beauty (b) quarks, which are copiously produced at the LHC: a factor 10,000 more are produced than at the current dedicated experiments (the B factories). The so-called CKM triangle is a theoretical representation of the way that quarks fit into the Standard Model. Like any triangle this CKM triangle has three sides and three angles that should add up to 180 degrees if the theory is correct. LHCb will be the first experiment with the capability to measure all the angles and sides of the CKM triangles in more than one decay channel and hence to fully test the Standard Model interpretation of CP violation. To isolate signals of new physics it is crucial to measure all the angles of the CKM triangle, particularly the weak phase angle gamma. This research proposal describes a work programme to measure the weak phase angle gamma using one specific decay channel (Bs-&amp;gt;K+K-) with the first data collected by the LHCb experiment. This work will culminate in the first measurement of the CKM triangle angle gamma at LHCb. This project spans the critical three year time period, October 2005 to October 2008, from the assembly of the detector to publishing the first physics result from the full system. PPARC has made a major investment in the design and construction of this experiment. I will use this fellowship to turn this UK leading detector expertise into UK physics results. Some of the most important LHCb physics results can be obtained with only a few months data. This is why my analysis must start to be developed in October 2005, eighteen months before collisions occur. The LHCb detector is specifically designed for the study of B meson decays. Two sub-detectors, largely built by the UK, are critical to the ability of LHCb to perform the measurement in the channel Bs-&amp;gt;K+K-: the silicon vertex locator (VELO) which measures the production and decay points of the Bs meson and the Ring Imaging Cherekov (RICH) detector that identifies the K+ and K- particles. I plan to spend the detector related component of my fellowship working on the VELO. The VELO is composed of 21 stations each comprised of two radiation hard silicon strip detectors placed along the beam direction. During stable running conditions, the sensors will be put only 8mm from the beam axis and an excellent resolution on the particle production and decay obtained. However the positions of the sensors need to be known with an accuracy of a few millionths of a metre (microns) or the performance will be degraded. I have been asked, subject to obtaining a suitably funded position, to take responsibility for the measurement at CERN of the assembled VELO system of the UK silicon modules in the mechanical frame. This complements the work of my colleagues in the Glasgow group who are already responsible for the software alignment of the detector. Afterwards, I will be particularly involved in determining the resolution of the silicon sesnors and translating this into the uncertainty on my physics measurement and other measurements made by the collaboration. Once I have developed my analysis and the detector is running I will be able to make my measurement with only a few months of data and make an important contribution to understanding the physics of CP Violation. So maybe I will be announcing a discovery of New Physics in early 2008!</gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-10-31</gtr:end><gtr:fun